her_name: Minor Basilica of St. Michael the Archangel
her_description: known as the Tayabas Basilica, is a historic Roman Catholic basilica and National Cultural Treasure located in Tayabas, Quezon, Philippines. It is known for having one of the longest naves among Spanish colonial era churches in the country and a unique key-shaped floor plan, earning it the local moniker "Susi ng Tayabas"

Known as the St. Joseph Chapel (or "Cementerio de
los Espa√±oles"), is a historic 18th-century cemetery chapel located on C.M Recto St. (Lucena Way) in Tayabas City, Quezon. It is recognized as a National Cultural Treasure by the National Museum. Built by the Spaniards in the 18th century (around 1855), it served as the burial place for the Spanish and Filipino elite. It is one of two historic cemetery chapels in the municipality.

Built between 1840 and 1850 in Tayabas, Quezon, using forced labor (polo y servicio) under the direction of Franciscan priest Fray Antonio Mateos. It is a fivespan stone arch bridge that was inaugurated in 1850 and is recognized as one of the longest bridges from the Spanish era. In 2011, it was declared a National Cultural Treasure.
